ungroup(25.10)                                                  ungroup(25.10)

Name
       ungroup - Ungroups the specified hinsts

Syntax
       ungroup

       [-help]

       [-check_only]

       <hInst>+

       [-exclude <hinst>+]

       [-flatten]

       [-honor_dont_touch]

       [-threshold <instance_count>]

       [-verbose]

       [-simple  | -prefix <prefix> | -escaped ]

       [-force | -only_user_hierarchy ]

       Ungroups  the  specified  hinsts.  Ungrouping  dissolves the hinsts and
       moves the contents into its parent directory. By default, an  hinst  or
       an  inst inside one of the ungrouped hinsts is renamed by concatenating
       its name to its parent's name with  "_".  for  example,  "ungroup  h1",
       would rename h1/i1 to h1_i1.  Name collisions are resolved by appending
       _1,  _2,  etc. until a unique name is found. If a given hinst cannot be
       ungrouped, a warning is issued about why it cannot be ungrouped.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each ungroup.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man ungroup

       <hInst>+
              Specifies the hinst(s) to be ungrouped.

       -check_only
              Checks  all constraints on the specified hinsts to be ungrouped.
              No actual ECO operation takes place.

       -escaped
              Flattened names use escaped hinst names.

              For example, h1/i1 becomes \h1/i1 in Verilog and h1\/i1 in DEF.

       -exclude <hinst>+
              Excludes specified hinst(s) as ungroup targets.

       -flatten
              Ungroups recursively below the specified hinst(s)

       -force Ungroups all hierarchy, mapped or not, and overrides ungroup_al-
              lowed if it is set to false.

       -honor_dont_touch
              Skips the hinst that is marked as dont touch.

       -only_user_hierarchy
              Ungroups only user hierarchy, synthesized module will not be un-
              grouped.

       -prefix <prefix>
              Flattened names use a prefix. For example, h1/i1  becomes  <pre-
              fix>_i1.

       -simple
              Flattened  names  use  the base_name. For example, h1/i1 becomes
              i1.

       -threshold <instance_count>
              Ungroups only those hinsts that have an instance count less than
              or equal to the specified integer.

       -verbose
              Prints the names of the hierarchies that are being ungrouped.

Example
              * The following command will flatten h1, h2/h3. It  will  recur-
                sively  flatten any lower hinsts that have an inst count <= 10
                and do not have `cpu' in their name.

                >ungroup {h1 h2/h3}  -exclude  *cpu*  -flatten  -threshold  10
                -prefix test

              *

                This command ungroups all hinsts matching h1* and uses escaped
                names  for the flattened names. This is useful so external SDC
                files that only refer to inst and pin names  will  still  work
                but  it  may  cause  problems in down-stream tools that do not
                support escaped names. Note that hpins and hnets of  ungrouped
                hinsts  will disappear, so usage of those names will no longer
                work.

                >ungroup h1* -escaped

                An inst named h1/i1 will become h1\/i1.  Various commands like
                get_cells will still "soft-match" h1/i1 to the escaped  h1\/i1
                name.

Related Information
              * group_instance_suffix

